<section xml:id="C27.S6">
<title>Divisor Sums</title>        
  
<para xml:id="C27.S6.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="1" xml:id="C27.S6.p1.s1">
Sums of number-theoretic functions extended over divisors are of special interest.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="2" xml:id="C27.S6.p1.s2">
For example, <Math equation-number="27.6.1" mode="display" xml:id="C27.S6.E1">\sum_{d\mathbin{|}n}\lambda\left(d\right)=\begin{cases}1,&amp;n\mbox{ is a square} ,\\ 0,&amp;\mbox{otherwise}.\end{cases</Math> }
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C27.S6.p2">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="3" xml:id="C27.S6.p2.s1">
If <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C27.S6.p2.m1">f</Math> is multiplicative, then <Math equation-number="27.6.2" mode="display" xml:id="C27.S6.E2">\sum_{d\mathbin{|}n}\mu\left(d\right)f(d)=\prod_{p\mathbin{|}n}(1-f(p)), if n&gt;1</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C27.S6.p3">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="4" xml:id="C27.S6.p3.s1">
Generating functions, Euler products, and MÃ¶bius inversion are used to evaluate many sums extended over divisors.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="5" xml:id="C27.S6.p3.s2">
Examples include: <Math equation-number="27.6.3" mode="display" xml:id="C27.S6.E3">\sum_{d\mathbin{|}n}|\mu\left(d\right)|=2^{\nu\left(n\right)},</Math> , <Math equation-number="27.6.4" mode="display" xml:id="C27.S6.E4">\sum_{d^{2}\mathbin{|}n}\mu\left(d\right)=|\mu\left(n\right)|,</Math> , <Math equation-number="27.6.5" mode="display" xml:id="C27.S6.E5">\sum_{d\mathbin{|}n}\frac{|\mu\left(d\right)|}{\phi\left(d\right)}=\frac{n}{ \phi\left(n\right)},</Math> <Math equation-number="27.6.6" mode="display" xml:id="C27.S6.E6">\sum_{d\mathbin{|}n}\phi_{k}\left(d\right)\left(\frac{n}{d}\right)^{k}=1^{k}+2 ^{k}+\dots+n^{k},</Math> <Math equation-number="27.6.7" mode="display" xml:id="C27.S6.E7">\sum_{d\mathbin{|}n}\mu\left(d\right)\left(\frac{n}{d}\right)^{k}=J_{k}\left(n \right),</Math> <Math equation-number="27.6.8" mode="display" xml:id="C27.S6.E8">\sum_{d\mathbin{|}n}J_{k}\left(d\right)=n^{k}</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
</section>
